ublic goods and services using original and unusual data this book uses post communist russia as a case in examining what the author calls this broader weak state syndrome in many developing countries through interviews with over 800 russian bureaucrats in 72 of russia's 89 provinces and a highly original database on patterns of regional government non compliance to federal law and policy the book demonstrates that resistance to russian central authority is not so much ethnically based as others have argued as much as generated by the will of powerful and wealthy regional political and economic actors seeking to protect assets they had acquired through russia's troubled transition out of communism download pdf+ excerpt chapter 1 modified june 2006 pdf resisting_the_state_ _excerpt pdf 638.9 kb parent research program on evaluating international influences on democratic development program topics russia search cddrl search within everything courses events fellowships news op eds people publications research other pages publications of interest partisan cleavages state retrenchment and free trade latin america in the 1990s beatriz magaloni vidal romero latin american research review vol 43 2 2008 pdf+ pigs wolves and the evolution of post soviet competitive authoritarianism 1992 2005 lucan a way steve levitsky cddrl working papers 2006 pdf+ american efforts at promoting regime change in the soviet union and then russia lessons learned michael a mcfaul cddrl working papers 2005 pdf+ accommodating ethnic differences in post soviet eurasia gail w lapidus crawford young mark beissinger woodrow wilson center and johns hopkins university press in beyond state crisis post colonial africa and post soviet eurasia in comparative perspective 2002 buy+ cover support map & directions contact rss+ rss xml feeds freeman spogli institute for international studies encina hall 616 serra st stanford ca 94305 6055 tel 650 723 4610 fax 650 725 2592 mail code 6055
